<h1 class="title">Predefined Rules</h1>
<span class="subtitle"></span>
<!-- $$$strules-predefined-rules.html-description -->
<div class="descr"> <a name="details"></a>
<a name="default-qt-configurations"></a>
<h2 id="default-qt-configurations">Default Qt Configurations</h2>
<p>ST specific rules overrides default <a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-predefined-rules.html">Qt configurations predefined in QS features</a>. Below a description of CONFIG values updated:</p>
<div class="table"><table class="generic">
 <thead><tr class="qt-style"><th  colspan="2" rowspan=" 1">Option</th><th >Description</th></tr>
<tr class="qt-style"><th  colspan="3" rowspan=" 1">Build Modes</th></tr></thead>
<tr valign="top" class="odd"><td ><code>+</code></td><td ><code>debug_and_release</code></td><td >Project built in both debug and release modes, regardless of platorm and build environment (except for auxiliary target).</td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="even"><td ><code>+</code></td><td ><code>build_all</code></td><td >Enables project built in both debug and release modes by default.</td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="odd"><td  colspan="3" rowspan=" 1"></td></tr>
<thead><tr class="qt-style"><th  colspan="3" rowspan=" 1">Compiler Options</th></tr></thead>
<tr valign="top" class="even"><td ><code>+</code></td><td ><code>precompile_header</code></td><td >Enables precompiled headers support.</td></tr>
</table></div>
<a name="additional-features"></a>
<h2 id="additional-features">Additional Features</h2>
<p>ST specific rules also provides following CONFIG additional features:</p>
<div class="table"><table class="generic">
 <thead><tr class="qt-style"><th >Option</th><th >Description</th></tr></thead>
<tr valign="top" class="odd"><td ><code>ldtools</code></td><td ><i>LDTools rules only:</i> enables LDTools-styled project by:<ul>
<li>assigning the value of <code>DESTDIR</code> to <code>$${<a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-variable-reference.html#installdir">INSTALLDIR</a>}/${<a href="strules-pseudo-variable-reference.html#build-mkspec">BUILD_MKSPEC</a>}/${<a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-pseudo-variable-reference.html#library-mode">LIBRARY_MODE</a>}/${<a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-pseudo-variable-reference.html#build-mode">BUILD_MODE</a>}</code>.</li>
<li>ignoring <code>INSTALLS</code> variable definitions (installation handled by LDTArtifact tool).</li>
<li>processing below LDTools custom file rules:<ul>
<li>optional package user rules <code>${<a href="strules-pseudo-variable-reference.html#package">PACKAGE</a>}/common.pri</code>.</li>
<li>optional manual sources definition <code>$${_PRO_FILE_PWD_}/_sources.pri</code>.</li>
<li>optional project extra rules <code>$${_PRO_FILE_PWD_}/_custom.pri</code>.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>adding LDTArtifact deployment tool as target post-link command.</li>
</ul>
</td></tr>
</table></div>
<a name="projects-package"></a>
<h2 id="projects-package">Projects Package</h2>
<p>A package represents a set of related projects delivered together. Each package directory has to include an installation directory (i.e&#x2e; a <code>Delivery</code> folder), and an optional source code directory containing all projects to build. Note that most of the time, a package will be equivalent to a Subversion repository.</p>
<p>Any project including ST specific rules must be defined inside a package to be processed by qmake tool.</p>
<a name="project-building"></a>
<h2 id="project-building">Project Building</h2>
<a name="target-definition"></a>
<h4 >Target Definition</h4>
<p>By default, binary target names are automatically suffixed by the <a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-predefined-rules.html#target-definition">debug modifier</a> <code>[d]</code>, if none is already applied. However, if target should have the same name in debug and release modes, suffixes it by the <code>[]</code> modifier in order to deactivate this mechanism.</p>
<p>Furthermore, ST specific rules initialize target <a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-variable-reference.html#properties">PROPERTIES</a> members as follows:</p>
<div class="table"><table class="generic">
 <thead><tr class="qt-style"><th >Member</th><th >Value</th><th >Notes</th></tr></thead>
<tr valign="top" class="odd"><td ><code>version</code></td><td ><code>$$(VERSION).$$(BUILDNUMBER)</code></td><td  rowspan=" 2">Jenkins variables <code>$$(NAME)</code>, <code>$$(VERSION)</code> and <code>$$(BUILDNUMBER)</code> are available when project is rebuilt via a Jenkins job.</td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="even"><td ><code>product</code></td><td ><code>$$(NAME)</code></td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="odd"><td  colspan="3" rowspan=" 1"></td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="even"><td ><code>company</code></td><td ><code>Diginext</code></td><td ></td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="odd"><td ><code>domain</code></td><td ><code>diginext.fr</code></td><td ></td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="even"><td ><code>copyright</code></td><td ><code>Copyright (C) %y %c</code></td><td >Will give when resolved: <code>Copyright (C) &lt;year&gt; Diginext</code>.</td></tr>
</table></div>
<a name="installation-definition"></a>
<h4 >Installation Definition</h4>
<p>Installation directory, defined by <a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-variable-reference.html#installdir">INSTALLDIR</a> variable, must point to <code>Delivery</code> directory of current package or one of its subdirectories. If not specified in your project file, this variable will be assigned to <code>${<a href="strules-pseudo-variable-reference.html#package">PACKAGE</a>}/Delivery</code> by default.</p>
<p>Moreover, <code>target.path</code> variable, defined in <code>INSTALLS</code> variables set, will be automatically assigned to <code>${<a href="strules-pseudo-variable-reference.html#build-mkspec">BUILD_MKSPEC</a>}/${<a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-pseudo-variable-reference.html#library-mode">LIBRARY_MODE</a>}/${<a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-pseudo-variable-reference.html#build-mode">BUILD_MODE</a>}</code> if not specified.</p>
<a name="compiler-options"></a>
<h4 >Compiler Options</h4>
<p>Binary target only. ST specific rules enhances <a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-predefined-rules.html#compiler-options">compiler and linker options defined in QS features</a>. Below table lists additional compilation rules implemented:</p>
<div class="table"><table class="generic">
 <thead><tr class="qt-style"><th >Scope</th><th >Value</th><th >Description</th></tr>
<tr class="qt-style"><th  colspan="3" rowspan=" 1">Preprocessor Macros</th></tr></thead>
<tr valign="top" class="odd"><td ></td><td ><code>$$<a href="../qsfeatures/mkspecs-replace-function-reference.html#target-mode">TARGET()</a>_LIB</code></td><td ><i>Shared library target only:</i> defines symbols import/export control macro.</td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="even"><td ><span class=nowrap>Windows based</span></td><td ><code>_WINDOWS</code> <br />
 <code>_WIN32_PLATEFORM_</code></td><td >Additional Windows 32/64 bits platform preprocessor macros.</td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="odd"><td >Linux based</td><td ><code>_LINUX_PLATEFORM_</code></td><td >Additional Linux platform preprocessor macro.</td></tr>
<tr valign="top" class="even"><td  colspan="3" rowspan=" 1"></td></tr>
<thead><tr class="qt-style"><th  colspan="3" rowspan=" 1">C/C++ Compiler Options</th></tr></thead>
<tr valign="top" class="odd"><td >Visual C++</td><td ><span class=nowrap><code>-Zc:strictStrings:none</code></span></td><td ><i><code>release</code> mode only</i>: enables string literal type conversion.</td></tr>
</table></div>
</div>
